1 WHEREAS, R.S. 46:1822 provides a framework for the reimbursement of forensic
2 medical examinations, ensuring that victims are not billed for the costs of evidence
3 collection; and
4 WHEREAS, there is a critical need to clarify and streamline the reimbursement
5 process to ensure that healthcare facilities and forensic examiners are promptly and fairly
6 compensated for the specialized exams provided to survivors of domestic violence; and
7 WHEREAS, the utilization of forensic medical examinations for survivors of
8 domestic violence not only aids in the judicial process but also provides victims with a
9 comprehensive medical record of their trauma, which is essential for long-term healing and
10 safety planning; and
11 WHEREAS, standardizing these examinations across the state would ensure that a
12 victim in a rural parish receives the same high quality of forensic care and evidence
13 preservation as a victim in a major metropolitan area.
14 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
15 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request the Louisiana Commission on Law
16 Enforcement and Administration of Criminal Justice to conduct a comprehensive review of
17 the statutory framework and administrative procedures in order to establish uniform
18 protocols for forensic medical examinations for survivors of domestic violence and to
19 provide a consistent source of reimbursement for these examinations.
20 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that in conducting this review, the Louisiana
21 Commission on Law Enforcement and Administration of Criminal Justice shall consider all
22 of the following:
23 (1) Identification of current efficiencies, deficiencies, and potential conflicts in
24 existing statutes and administrative procedures relative to forensic medical examinations.
25 (2) Development of recommendations for uniform protocols to ensure that forensic
26 medical examinations for survivors of domestic violence are administered and available
27 across the state in a consistent manner.
28 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Louisiana Commission on Law Enforcement
29 and Administration of Criminal Justice may receive testimony, feedback, input, and data
30 from all of the following:
